How to track changes in the meaning of words over time.
View this email in your browser (http://mailchi.mp/onelanday/the-morning-p=
aper-dynamic-word-embeddings-for-evolving-semantic-discovery?e=3D1c7444593b)
This paper write-up is also available online at The Morning Paper. (http:/=
/blog.acolyer.org/2018/02/22/dynamic-word-embeddings-for-evolving-semantic=
-discovery)


** the morning paper
------------------------------------------------------------


** Dynamic word embeddings for evolving semantic discovery
------------------------------------------------------------

Dynamic word embeddings for evolving semantic discovery (https://arxiv.org=
/abs/1703.00607) Yao et al.=2C WSDM=E2=80=9918

One of the most popular posts on this blog is my introduction to word embe=
ddings with word2vec (=E2=80=98The amazing power of word vectors (https://=
blog.acolyer.org/2016/04/21/the-amazing-power-of-word-vectors/) =E2=80=99)=
=2E In today=E2=80=99s paper choice Yao et al. introduce a lovely extension=
 that enables you to track how the meaning of words changes over time. It=
 would be a superb tool for analysing brands for example.

Human language is an evolving construct=2C with word semantic associations=
 changing over time. For example=2C apple which was traditionally only ass=
ociated with fruits=2C is now also associated with a technology company. S=
imilarly the association of names of famous personalities (e.g.=2C trump)=
 changes with a change in their roles. For this reason=2C understanding an=
d tracking word evolution is useful for time-aware knowledge extraction ta=
sks....

Let=E2=80=99s go straight to some examples of what we=E2=80=99re talking a=
bout here:

(Enlarge (https://adriancolyer.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/evolving-word-e=
mbeddings-fig-1.jpeg) )

Consider the trajectory of =E2=80=98apple=E2=80=99: in 1994 it=E2=80=99s m=
ost closely associated with fruits=2C and by 2000 changing dietary associa=
tions can be seen=2C and apple is associated with the less healthy =E2=80=
=98cake=2C=E2=80=99 =E2=80=98tart=2C=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98cream.=E2=80=99=
 From 2005 through 2016 though=2C the word is strongly associated with App=
le the company=2C and moreover you can see the changing associations with=
 Apple over time=2C from =E2=80=98iTunes=E2=80=99 to Google=2C Microsoft=
=2C Samsung et al..

Likewise =E2=80=98amazon=E2=80=99 moves from a river to the company Amazon=
=2C and =E2=80=98Obama=E2=80=99 moves from his pre-presidential roles to p=
resident=2C as does =E2=80=98Trump.=E2=80=99

These embeddings are learned from articles in The New York Times between 1=
990 and 2016. The results are really interesting (we=E2=80=99ll see more f=
un things you can do with them shortly)=2C but you might be wondering why=
 this is hard to do. Why not simply divide up the articles in the corpus (=
e.g.=2C by year)=2C learn word embeddings for each partition (which we kno=
w how to do)=2C and then compare them?

What makes this complicated is that when you learn an embedding for a word=
 in one time window (e.g.=2C =E2=80=98bank=E2=80=99)=2C there=E2=80=99s no=
 guarantee that the embedding will match that in another time window=2C ev=
en if there is no semantic change in the meaning of the word across the tw=
o. So the meaning of =E2=80=98bank=E2=80=99 in 1990 and 1995 could be subs=
tantially the same=2C and yet the learned embeddings might not be. This is=
 known as the alignment problem.

A key practical issue of learning different word embeddings for different=
 time periods is alignment. Specifically=2C most cost functions for traini=
ng are invariant to rotations=2C as a byproduct=2C the learned embeddings=
 across time may not be placed in the same latent space.

Prior approaches to solving this problem first use independent learning as=
 per our straw man=2C and then post process the embeddings in an alignment=
 phase to try and match them up. But Yao et al. have found a way to learn=
 temporal embeddings in all time slices concurrently=2C doing away with th=
e need for a separate alignment phase. The experimental results suggests t=
hat this yields better outcomes that the prior two-step methods=2C and the=
 approach is also robust against data sparsity (it will tolerate time slic=
es where some words are rarely present or even missing).


** Temporal word embeddings
------------------------------------------------------------

Recall that underpinning word embeddings is the idea of a co-occurrence ma=
trix (see =E2=80=98GloVe: Global vectors for word representation (https://=
blog.acolyer.org/2016/04/22/glove-global-vectors-for-word-representation/)=
 =E2=80=99) capturing the pointwise mutual information (PMI) between any t=
wo words in the vocabulary. Given a corpus \mathcal{D} =2C we can compute=
 a PMI matrix using windows of size L (around the word in question)=2C whe=
re the entry at (w=2Cc) for words w and_c_ is given by:

$PMI(=2CL)_{w=2Cc} =3D ( ) $

Where \#(w=2Cc) counts the number of times that words w and c co-occur wit=
hin a window of size L in corpus \mathcal{D} and \#(w) and \#(c) count the=
 number of occurences of w and c in the corpus respectively.

The learned embedding vectors for w and c=2C u_w and u_c =2C are such that=
 u_{w}^{T}u_c \approx PMI(\mathcal{D}=2CL)_{w=2Cc} .

Adding a temporal dimension to this=2C for each time slice t the positive=
 PMI matrix PPMI(t=2CL) is defined as :

\displaystyle PPMI(t=2CL)_{w=2Cc} =3D \max\{ PMI(\mathcal{D}_t=2CL)_{w=2Cc=
}=2C 0 \} :=3D Y(t)

And the temporal word embeddings U(t) must satisfy U(t)U(t)^T \approx PPMI=
(t=2CL) .

This still doesn=E2=80=99t solve the alignment problem though. To encourag=
e alignment=2C the authors cast finding temporal word embeddings as the so=
lution to the following joint optimisation problem:

where Y(t) =3D PPMI(t=2CL) and \lambda=2C \tau are configurable parameters=
 greater than zero.
* The penalty term ||U(t)||^{2}_{F} enforces low-rank data fidelity as has=
 been widely adopted in previous work
* The smoothing term || U(t-1) - U(t) ||^{2}_{F} encourages the word embed=
dings to align. The parameter \tau controls how fast the embeddings can ch=
ange over time.

This is decomposed to solve the objective function across time for each U(=
t) =2C using block coordinate descent (BCD) which minimises with respect t=
o a single block (U(t) ) at a time. In theory BCD lacks convergence guaran=
tees=2C but in practice it seems to work well. You could always swap BCD f=
or e.g. SGD if you wanted to (but it would make slower progress).


** Finding equivalent terms over time
------------------------------------------------------------

Let=E2=80=99s return to the fun things you can do with the resulting embed=
dings. Here=E2=80=99s an example of finding conceptually equivalent items=
 or people over time. For example=2C the closest equivalent to the =E2=80=
=99iPhone=E2=80=99 as of 2012 was =E2=80=98pc=E2=80=99 in 2003=2C and by 2=
013-16 it was =E2=80=98smartphone.=E2=80=99 Likewise back in 1990-94 the e=
quivalents of twitter were =E2=80=98broadcast=E2=80=99=2C =E2=80=98cnn=E2=
=80=99=2C =E2=80=98radio=E2=80=99 etc.. In the =E2=80=98mp3=E2=80=99 colum=
n you can clearly see associations with the dominant form of music consump=
tion in the given time periods.

We can do a similar thing asking who played a certain political role in a=
 given year:

Even more impressive=2C is this search for equivalence in sport by looking=
 for the ATP No. 1 ranked male tennis player in a given year. Here we=E2=
=80=99re asking=2C who played the same role that Nadal did in the year 201=
0?


** Tracking popularity over time
------------------------------------------------------------

The learned word vector norms across times grow with word frequency=2C and=
 can be viewed as a time series for detecting trending concepts with more=
 robustness than word frequency.

Generally=2C comparing to frequencies which are more sporadic and noisy=2C=
 we note that the norm of our embeddings encourages smoothness and normali=
zation while being indicative of the periods when the corresponding words=
 were making news rounds.

Here=E2=80=99s a comparison of norms (top chart) and word frequency (botto=
m chart) for the names of US presidents over time.


** The last word
------------------------------------------------------------

Our proposed method simultaneously learns the embeddings and aligns them a=
cross time=2C and has several benefits: higher interpretability for embedd=
ings=2C better quality with less data=2C and more reliable alignment for a=
cross-time querying.

