<h1 style=3D"margin: 0;padding: 0;display: block;font-family: Helvetica;fo=
nt-size: 40px;font-style: normal;font-weight: bold;line-height: 125%;lette=
r-spacing: -1px;text-align: left;color: #606060 !important;">the morning p=
aper</h1>

<h2 id=3D"dynamic-word-embeddings-for-evolving-semantic-discovery" style=
=3D"margin: 0;padding: 0;display: block;font-family: Helvetica;font-size:=
 26px;font-style: normal;font-weight: bold;line-height: 125%;letter-spacin=
g: -.75px;text-align: left;color: #404040 !important;">Dynamic word embedd=
ings for evolving semantic discovery</h2>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;"><a href=3D"https://acolyer.us9.list-=
manage.com/track/click?u=3D4188b6afbe9e5d43111fef4d4&id=3Db1c50d4def&e=3D=
1c7444593b" style=3D"word-wrap: break-word;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-web=
kit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;font-weight: normal;text-decorat=
ion: underline;">Dynamic word embeddings for evolving semantic discovery</=
a> Yao et al.=2C <em>WSDM=E2=80=9918</em></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">One of the most popular posts on thi=
s blog is my introduction to word embeddings with word2vec (=E2=80=98<a hr=
ef=3D"https://acolyer.us9.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D4188b6afbe9e5d43=
111fef4d4&id=3D07f0d829fe&e=3D1c7444593b" style=3D"word-wrap: break-word;=
-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;f=
ont-weight: normal;text-decoration: underline;">The amazing power of word=
 vectors</a>=E2=80=99). In today=E2=80=99s paper choice Yao et al. introdu=
ce a lovely extension that enables you to track how the meaning of words c=
hanges over time. It would be a superb tool for analysing brands for examp=
le.</p>
<blockquote style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust:=
 100%;display: block;padding: 20px 20px 10px 45px;margin: 20px 0px;font-st=
yle: italic;font-size: 14px;color: #141310;background: url(blog.acolyer.or=
g/wp-content/themes/pub/vigilance/images/blockquote.gif) no-repeat scroll=
 left top #E7E6E2;">
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Human language is an evolving constr=
uct=2C with word semantic associations changing over time. For example=2C=
 <code>apple</code> which was traditionally only associated with fruits=2C=
 is now also associated with a technology company. Similarly the associati=
on of names of famous personalities (e.g.=2C <code>trump</code>) changes w=
ith a change in their roles. For this reason=2C understanding and tracking=
 word evolution is useful for time-aware knowledge extraction tasks....</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Let=E2=80=99s go straight to some ex=
amples of what we=E2=80=99re talking about here:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;"><img src=3D"https://adriancolyer.fil=
es.wordpress.com/2018/02/evolving-word-embeddings-fig-1.jpeg?w=3D640" styl=
e=3D"border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode:=
 bicubic;height: auto !important;"> (<a href=3D"https://acolyer.us9.list-m=
anage.com/track/click?u=3D4188b6afbe9e5d43111fef4d4&id=3D0184e12340&e=3D=
1c7444593b" style=3D"word-wrap: break-word;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webk=
it-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;font-weight: normal;text-decorati=
on: underline;">Enlarge</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Consider the trajectory of =E2=80=98=
apple=E2=80=99: in 1994 it=E2=80=99s most closely associated with fruits=
=2C and by 2000 changing dietary associations can be seen=2C and apple is=
 associated with the less healthy =E2=80=98cake=2C=E2=80=99 =E2=80=98tart=
=2C=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98cream.=E2=80=99 From 2005 through 2016 though=2C=
 the word is strongly associated with Apple the company=2C and moreover yo=
u can see the changing associations with Apple over time=2C from =E2=80=98=
iTunes=E2=80=99 to Google=2C Microsoft=2C Samsung et al..</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Likewise =E2=80=98amazon=E2=80=99 mo=
ves from a river to the company Amazon=2C and =E2=80=98Obama=E2=80=99 move=
s from his pre-presidential roles to president=2C as does =E2=80=98Trump.=
=E2=80=99</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">These embeddings are learned from ar=
ticles in The New York Times between 1990 and 2016. The results are really=
 interesting (we=E2=80=99ll see more fun things you can do with them short=
ly)=2C but you might be wondering why this is hard to do. Why not simply d=
ivide up the articles in the corpus (e.g.=2C by year)=2C learn word embedd=
ings for each partition (which we know how to do)=2C and then compare them=
?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">What makes this complicated is that=
 when you learn an embedding for a word in one time window (e.g.=2C =E2=80=
=98bank=E2=80=99)=2C there=E2=80=99s no guarantee that the embedding will=
 match that in another time window=2C <em>even if there is no semantic cha=
nge in the meaning of the word across the two</em>. So the meaning of =E2=
=80=98bank=E2=80=99 in 1990 and 1995 could be substantially the same=2C an=
d yet the learned embeddings might not be. This is known as the <em>alignm=
ent</em> problem.</p>
<blockquote style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust:=
 100%;display: block;padding: 20px 20px 10px 45px;margin: 20px 0px;font-st=
yle: italic;font-size: 14px;color: #141310;background: url(blog.acolyer.or=
g/wp-content/themes/pub/vigilance/images/blockquote.gif) no-repeat scroll=
 left top #E7E6E2;">
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">A key practical issue of learning di=
fferent word embeddings for different time periods is alignment. Specifica=
lly=2C most cost functions for training are invariant to rotations=2C as a=
 byproduct=2C the learned embeddings across time may not be placed in the=
 same latent space.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Prior approaches to solving this pro=
blem first use independent learning as per our straw man=2C and then post=
 process the embeddings in an alignment phase to try and match them up. Bu=
t Yao et al. have found a way to learn temporal embeddings in all time sli=
ces concurrently=2C doing away with the need for a separate alignment phas=
e. The experimental results suggests that this yields better outcomes that=
 the prior two-step methods=2C and the approach is also robust against dat=
a sparsity (it will tolerate time slices where some words are rarely prese=
nt or even missing).</p>
<h3 id=3D"temporal-word-embeddings" style=3D"margin: 0;padding: 0;display:=
 block;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 18px;font-style: normal;font-weig=
ht: bold;line-height: 125%;letter-spacing: -.5px;text-align: left;color: #=
606060 !important;">Temporal word embeddings</h3>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Recall that underpinning word embedd=
ings is the idea of a co-occurrence matrix (see =E2=80=98<a href=3D"https:=
//acolyer.us9.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D4188b6afbe9e5d43111fef4d4&id=
=3D47aee50cc4&e=3D1c7444593b" style=3D"word-wrap: break-word;-ms-text-siz=
e-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #6DC6DD;font-weight:=
 normal;text-decoration: underline;">GloVe: Global vectors for word repres=
entation</a>=E2=80=99) capturing the <em>pointwise mutual information</em>=
 (PMI) between any two words in the vocabulary. Given a corpus <img style=
=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-=
ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://la=
tex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D" alt=3D"\mathcal{D}" title=3D=
"\mathcal{D}">=2C we can compute a PMI matrix using windows of size L (aro=
und the word in question)=2C where the entry at (<em>w</em>=2C<em>c</em>)=
 for words <em>w</em> and_c_ is given by:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">$PMI(=2CL)_{w=2Cc} =3D (  ) $</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Where <img style=3D"vertical-align:=
 middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mo=
de: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/pn=
g.latex?%5C%23%28w%2Cc%29" alt=3D"\#(w=2Cc)" title=3D"\#(w=2Cc)"> counts t=
he number of times that words <em>w</em> and <em>c</em> co-occur within a=
 window of size L in corpus <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0=
;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;heigh=
t: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathca=
l%7BD%7D" alt=3D"\mathcal{D}" title=3D"\mathcal{D}"> and <img style=3D"ver=
tical-align: middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-inte=
rpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.cod=
ecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%23%28w%29" alt=3D"\#(w)" title=3D"\#(w)"> and <img=
 style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration:=
 none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"htt=
ps://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5C%23%28c%29" alt=3D"\#(c)" title=3D"\#=
(c)"> count the number of occurences of <em>w</em> and <em>c</em> in the c=
orpus respectively.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">The learned embedding vectors for <e=
m>w</em> and <em>c</em>=2C <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;=
outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height=
: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?u_w" alt=
=3D"u_w" title=3D"u_w"> and <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0=
;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;heigh=
t: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?u_c" alt=
=3D"u_c" title=3D"u_c">=2C are such that <img style=3D"vertical-align: mid=
dle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode:=
 bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.l=
atex?u_%7Bw%7D%5E%7BT%7Du_c%20%5Capprox%20PMI%28%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%2CL%29_%=
7Bw%2Cc%7D" alt=3D"u_{w}^{T}u_c \approx PMI(\mathcal{D}=2CL)_{w=2Cc}" titl=
e=3D"u_{w}^{T}u_c \approx PMI(\mathcal{D}=2CL)_{w=2Cc}">.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Adding a temporal dimension to this=
=2C for each time slice <em>t</em> the <em>positive PMI matrix</em> <img s=
tyle=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: no=
ne;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https:=
//latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?PPMI%28t%2CL%29" alt=3D"PPMI(t=2CL)" title=
=3D"PPMI(t=2CL)"> is defined as :</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;"><img style=3D"vertical-align: middle=
;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bic=
ubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex=
?%5Cdisplaystyle%20PPMI%28t%2CL%29_%7Bw%2Cc%7D%20%3D%20%5Cmax%5C%7B%20PMI%=
28%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D_t%2CL%29_%7Bw%2Cc%7D%2C%200%20%5C%7D%20%3A%3D%20Y%28t%=
29" alt=3D"\displaystyle PPMI(t=2CL)_{w=2Cc} =3D \max\{ PMI(\mathcal{D}_t=
=2CL)_{w=2Cc}=2C 0 \} :=3D Y(t)" title=3D"\displaystyle PPMI(t=2CL)_{w=2Cc=
} =3D \max\{ PMI(\mathcal{D}_t=2CL)_{w=2Cc}=2C 0 \} :=3D Y(t)"></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">And the temporal word embeddings <im=
g style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration:=
 none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"htt=
ps://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U%28t%29" alt=3D"U(t)" title=3D"U(t)"> m=
ust satisfy <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;outline: none;t=
ext-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !importa=
nt;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U%28t%29U%28t%29%5ET%20%5=
Capprox%20PPMI%28t%2CL%29" alt=3D"U(t)U(t)^T \approx PPMI(t=2CL)" title=3D=
"U(t)U(t)^T \approx PPMI(t=2CL)">.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">This still doesn=E2=80=99t solve the=
 alignment problem though. To encourage alignment=2C the authors cast find=
ing temporal word embeddings as the solution to the following joint optimi=
sation problem:</p>
<div class=3D"figure">
<img src=3D"https://adriancolyer.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/evolving-word=
-embeddings-eqn-5.jpeg?w=3D520" style=3D"border: 0;outline: none;text-deco=
ration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;">

</div>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">where <img style=3D"vertical-align:=
 middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mo=
de: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/pn=
g.latex?Y%28t%29%20%3D%20PPMI%28t%2CL%29" alt=3D"Y(t) =3D PPMI(t=2CL)" tit=
le=3D"Y(t) =3D PPMI(t=2CL)"> and <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;bord=
er: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;=
height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cl=
ambda%2C%20%5Ctau" alt=3D"\lambda=2C \tau" title=3D"\lambda=2C \tau"> are=
 configurable parameters greater than zero.</p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;">T=
he <em>penalty term</em> <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;ou=
tline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height:=
 auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%7C%7CU%28t=
%29%7C%7C%5E%7B2%7D_%7BF%7D" alt=3D"||U(t)||^{2}_{F}" title=3D"||U(t)||^{2=
}_{F}"> enforces low-rank data fidelity as has been widely adopted in prev=
ious work</li>
<li style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;">T=
he <em>smoothing term</em> <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;=
outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height=
: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%7C%7C%20U=
%28t-1%29%20-%20U%28t%29%20%7C%7C%5E%7B2%7D_%7BF%7D" alt=3D"|| U(t-1) - U(=
t) ||^{2}_{F}" title=3D"|| U(t-1) - U(t) ||^{2}_{F}"> encourages the word=
 embeddings to align. The parameter <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;b=
order: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicub=
ic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%=
5Ctau" alt=3D"\tau" title=3D"\tau"> controls how fast the embeddings can c=
hange over time.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">This is decomposed to solve the obje=
ctive function across time for each <img style=3D"vertical-align: middle;b=
order: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicub=
ic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?U=
%28t%29" alt=3D"U(t)" title=3D"U(t)">=2C using <em>block coordinate descen=
t</em> (BCD) which minimises with respect to a single block (<img style=3D=
"vertical-align: middle;border: 0;outline: none;text-decoration: none;-ms-=
interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;" src=3D"https://latex=
=2Ecodecogs.com/png.latex?U%28t%29" alt=3D"U(t)" title=3D"U(t)">) at a time.=
 In theory BCD lacks convergence guarantees=2C but in practice it seems to=
 work well. You could always swap BCD for e.g. SGD if you wanted to (but i=
t would make slower progress).</p>
<h3 id=3D"finding-equivalent-terms-over-time" style=3D"margin: 0;padding:=
 0;display: block;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 18px;font-style: norma=
l;font-weight: bold;line-height: 125%;letter-spacing: -.5px;text-align: le=
ft;color: #606060 !important;">Finding equivalent terms over time</h3>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Let=E2=80=99s return to the fun thin=
gs you can do with the resulting embeddings. Here=E2=80=99s an example of=
 finding <em>conceptually equivalent items or people over time</em>. For e=
xample=2C the closest equivalent to the =E2=80=99iPhone=E2=80=99 as of 201=
2 was =E2=80=98pc=E2=80=99 in 2003=2C and by 2013-16 it was =E2=80=98smart=
phone.=E2=80=99 Likewise back in 1990-94 the equivalents of twitter were=
 =E2=80=98broadcast=E2=80=99=2C =E2=80=98cnn=E2=80=99=2C =E2=80=98radio=E2=
=80=99 etc.. In the =E2=80=98mp3=E2=80=99 column you can clearly see assoc=
iations with the dominant form of music consumption in the given time peri=
ods.</p>
<div class=3D"figure">
<img src=3D"https://adriancolyer.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/evolving-word=
-embeddings-table-1.jpeg?w=3D480" style=3D"border: 0;outline: none;text-de=
coration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;">

</div>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">We can do a similar thing asking who=
 played a certain political role in a given year:</p>
<div class=3D"figure">
<img src=3D"https://adriancolyer.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/evolving-word=
-embeddings-table-2.jpeg?w=3D480" style=3D"border: 0;outline: none;text-de=
coration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;">

</div>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Even more impressive=2C is this sear=
ch for equivalence in sport by looking for the ATP No. 1 ranked male tenni=
s player in a given year. Here we=E2=80=99re asking=2C who played the same=
 role that Nadal did in the year 2010?</p>
<div class=3D"figure">
<img src=3D"https://adriancolyer.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/evolving-word=
-embeddings-table-3.jpeg?w=3D480" style=3D"border: 0;outline: none;text-de=
coration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;">

</div>
<h3 id=3D"tracking-popularity-over-time" style=3D"margin: 0;padding: 0;dis=
play: block;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 18px;font-style: normal;font=
-weight: bold;line-height: 125%;letter-spacing: -.5px;text-align: left;col=
or: #606060 !important;">Tracking popularity over time</h3>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">The learned word vector norms across=
 times grow with word frequency=2C and can be viewed as a time series for=
 detecting trending concepts with more robustness than word frequency.</p>
<blockquote style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust:=
 100%;display: block;padding: 20px 20px 10px 45px;margin: 20px 0px;font-st=
yle: italic;font-size: 14px;color: #141310;background: url(blog.acolyer.or=
g/wp-content/themes/pub/vigilance/images/blockquote.gif) no-repeat scroll=
 left top #E7E6E2;">
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Generally=2C comparing to frequencie=
s which are more sporadic and noisy=2C we note that the norm of our embedd=
ings encourages smoothness and normalization while being indicative of the=
 periods when the corresponding words were making news rounds.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Here=E2=80=99s a comparison of norms=
 (top chart) and word frequency (bottom chart) for the names of US preside=
nts over time.</p>
<div class=3D"figure">
<img src=3D"https://adriancolyer.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/evolving-word=
-embeddings-fig-2.jpeg?w=3D520" style=3D"border: 0;outline: none;text-deco=
ration: none;-ms-interpolation-mode: bicubic;height: auto !important;">

</div>
<h3 id=3D"the-last-word" style=3D"margin: 0;padding: 0;display: block;font=
-family: Helvetica;font-size: 18px;font-style: normal;font-weight: bold;li=
ne-height: 125%;letter-spacing: -.5px;text-align: left;color: #606060 !imp=
ortant;">The last word</h3>
<blockquote style=3D"-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-text-size-adjust:=
 100%;display: block;padding: 20px 20px 10px 45px;margin: 20px 0px;font-st=
yle: italic;font-size: 14px;color: #141310;background: url(blog.acolyer.or=
g/wp-content/themes/pub/vigilance/images/blockquote.gif) no-repeat scroll=
 left top #E7E6E2;">
<p style=3D"margin: 1em 0;padding: 0;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;-webkit-te=
xt-size-adjust: 100%;color: #606060;font-family: Helvetica;font-size: 15px=
;line-height: 150%;text-align: left;">Our proposed method simultaneously l=
earns the embeddings and aligns them across time=2C and has several benefi=
ts: higher interpretability for embeddings=2C better quality with less dat=
a=2C and more reliable alignment for across-time querying.</p>
</blockquote>


